hape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Joux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien.","French (northern) and Walloon: topographic name from French <i>houx</i> ‘holly’, or a habitational name from any of the places called with this word, for example in Eure-et-Loir (France) and in the province of Namur in Belgium (Wallonia).","German: rare northern variant of   Haux   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Haux","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz.","German: patronymic from   Hauck  ."]}]},{"name":"Ermentrude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, adopted from Old French by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It is derived from <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’ + <i>traut</i> ‘beloved’. It did not survive long into the Middle Ages, but was occasionally revived in the 18th and 19th centuries. It is now completely out of fashion."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ermentrude de Grandison de Joux was born in 1090, her father, Baron Conan 'Falko de La Sarraz' de Grandson, was 44 and her mother, Aelis de Ramerupt, was 42. She married Comte Henri I de Grandpré in 1110, in La Sarraz, Bern, Switzerland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1187."},"et":{"1090–after 1187":"1090–pärast 1187","1087–1132":"1087–1132","1090–1187":"1090–1187","1094–Male":"1094–Surnud","1087–Female":"1087–Surnud","1098–Male":"1098–Surnud","1104–1160":"1104–1160","–1114":"–1114","–1158":"–1158","1070–1150":"1070–1150","1110–1188":"1110–1188","1046–1114":"1046–1114","1049–1114":"1049–1114","1090":"1090","1110":"1110","1187":"1187","1132":"1132","1098":"1098","1087":"1087","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1094":"1094","1070":"1070","ABT 1150":"umbes 1150","1049":"1049","1104":"1104","1114":"1114